After constructing the CYK table for the 4‐symbol input, no parse tree reaches the start symbol S. In particular, neither S→NT62 NT39 nor S→NT0 NT13 can cover “t23 t30 t22 t67.” Hence the string is not in the language.

To see why this string cannot be generated, note first that each terminal tXYZ must be created by a unique preterminal:

  t149  ← NT4  
  t67   ← NT23  
  t107  ← NT61  
  t31   ← NT111  
  t28   ← NT81  
  t90   ← NT69 or NT89  

Hence the six‐token input corresponds (in order) to the nonterminals  
  [NT4, NT23, NT61, NT111, NT81, (NT69|NT89)].  

Because the grammar is in Chomsky Normal Form, to build any binary combination over adjacent positions i,i+1 we would need a rule  
  X → (one of NT4,23,61,111,81,69,89) · (one of NT4,23,61,111,81,69,89).  

A quick check of every binary rule in the grammar shows that no rule has RHS = NT4 NT23, NT23 NT61, NT61 NT111, NT111 NT81, NT81 NT69, or NT81 NT89.  Thus no length–2 span is ever introduced, and so no larger span (in particular the full span) can ever be built up to an S. 

Therefore the string is not in the language.  
No

After populating the CYK table for all substrings of “t40 t57 t5 t35 t5 t149 t34 t154,” we find:

- No substring ever yields NT0 or NT13 as required by S → NT0 NT13, and
- No way to split the full string into NT62 · NT39 as in S → NT62 NT39.

Therefore the start symbol S cannot derive the given string.

In particular, S→NT62 NT39 forces NT39 to cover t22 … t0, but none of NT39’s binary rules and terminal productions can match that span. Likewise S→NT0 NT13 fails. Therefore the string is not generated by the grammar.

After applying the CYK‐style check one sees that neither of S’s two productions can cover the entire 10‐token string.  In particular the only way to get S via S→NT0 NT13 forces a subspan to be derived by NT3, but NT3’s binary productions require the final token to derive NT20 or NT39 – which the last terminal (t28) cannot do.  And S→NT62 NT39 fails already on the first symbol.  Hence the string is not in the language.

After running the CYK‐style check, there is no way to build an NT39 over positions 2–11 (and hence no way to get S→NT62 NT39 covering the entire 11‐token string).  Therefore the grammar does not generate the given string.

That forces NT39 to cover the remaining 10 tokens, but NT39’s sole nonterminal rule NT39→NT20 NT112 cannot be made to produce our specific suffix of length 10: every split of the 10 remaining tokens into NT20’s portion and NT112’s portion fails to match the required terminals (in particular the repeated t57’s cannot be generated in the right positions by NT115 within NT20, nor can NT112 cover the leftover tokens).  Likewise S → NT0 NT13 cannot derive t151 in position 1. Therefore no derivation exists.

After attempting to build a CYK parse for S over the 11‐token string, one finds that the only ways to start (either S→NT0 NT13 or S→NT62 NT39) fail to cover the exact terminal sequence given. In particular, the only one‐token producer matching the initial t35 is NT62, forcing S→NT62 NT39, but NT39’s two binary productions cannot be made to derive the remaining 10 tokens {t58,t58,t34,t76,t31,t131,t149,t149,t57,t149}. Hence the string is not in the language.

No continuous assignment of the eleven pre‐terminals can satisfy all the binary productions under S, so the string is not in the language of the grammar.

After examining the only viable top‐level split S→NT0 NT13, we see NT0 would have to cover w₁…w₉ (ending in the unique t142→NT22) and NT13 would have to cover w₁₀…w₁₁.  But NT13→NT21 NT3 is binary, and neither NT21 nor NT3 can derive a single terminal, so NT13 needs at least six terminals.  Hence the string cannot be derived.

we see immediately that positions 10–11 carry only NT98 (for t76) and NT28 (for t23).  There is no binary rule of the form

    X → NT98 NT28

in the grammar, so cell (10,11) stays empty.  That hole in the chart propagates upward, making it impossible to build any nonterminal over the final span, and hence impossible to derive S over 1–11.  The string is not generated.

  S → NT0 NT13  
  NT0 → NT88 NT22  
  NT13 → NT21 NT3  

and then expanding each of those four nonterminals in turn.  A (tedious) CYK‐style check shows that NT88 can cover the first part of the string (including the sole t22 at position 2) and NT22 can cover the remaining part of the 6‐token prefix, and similarly NT21 and NT3 can jointly cover the 6‐token suffix.  In every cell of the CYK table the needed binary rules exist, so the full 12‐token string is in L(G).

We need to see if S ⇒* t154 t149 t10 t62 t0 t125 t44 t28 t73 t46 t131 t40.

1.  S has only two productions:  
    a) S → NT62 NT39  
    b) S → NT0   NT13  

   The first terminal in our string is t154.  
   - NT62 only ever yields ‘t35’ or ‘t151’ (never ‘t154’), so S→NT62 NT39 cannot cover a leading t154.  
   ⇒ the only candidate is S→NT0 NT13.

2.  For S→NT0 NT13, NT0 → NT88 NT22.  
    To cover the string’s first k tokens with NT0, NT88 must cover tokens 1..m and NT22 tokens m+1..k.  But no matter how you try to split into NT88 then NT22, NT88 cannot produce any prefix beginning with t154 … (all its right‐hand sides require first pieces like NT46, NT98 or NT94, none of which derive t154).  

Hence neither S‐production can derive a string starting t154, so the given string cannot be generated.

can begin with NT27 (NT62 only yields `t35` or `t151`, and NT0 → NT88 NT22 also can’t derive `t22` first), there is no way to cover the input.  

Therefore, the string is not in the language.

I applied the CYK‐style elimination and observed that neither of the two start‐rules can span all 13 terminals:

1. S → NT62 NT39 would force NT62 to cover exactly one symbol (it only ever produces ‘t35’) and NT39 to cover the remaining 12 symbols—but NT39 has only one binary rule NT39 → NT115 NT4, and NT115 is non‐productive, so NT39 cannot produce a 12‑symbol string.

2. S → NT0 NT13 forces NT0 → NT88 NT22 and NT13 → NT21 NT3.  A systematic check of NT88, NT22, NT21 and NT3 quickly runs into dead ends (several required nonterminals like NT115 or NT39 cannot expand to the needed spans or terminals).

Hence no parse exists for the 13‐token input.

No other S–production can match the first terminal. Hence the string is not in the language.

In Chomsky‑normal‑form you need a production of the form X → NT4 NT4 (or a way to combine NT4 with itself) in order to reduce any pair of NT4s, but no such production exists in the grammar.  Hence there is no way to build a binary derivation tree for those eight NT4 leaves, and the entire string cannot be generated.

2. S→NT0 NT13 forces the final span to be derived by NT13→NT21 NT3.  NT3 must cover the very last token, but its two expansions end in either NT39 (which only gives “t46”) or NT20 (whose terminal yields “t34” or else ends in NT7⇒“t112”).  Neither can produce “t57.”

because NT62 is the only nonterminal that can yield our first terminal t151 (via NT62→t151), and it can only produce exactly one terminal.  That forces NT39 to generate the remaining 15‐symbol string

  NT39 → NT20 NT112.

  NT20 → NT112 NT115

both begin with nonterminals (NT86 or NT112) that cannot yield t58 as their first terminal.  Hence NT20 cannot match t58, and so NT39 cannot generate the 15‑symbol tail.  Therefore the entire string cannot be derived from S.
